<br>
Regarding the Staff, and <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> uber</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->loot in general.  You see, there again, you help demonstrate MY case.  Loot distribution the high level isn't random because you're not getting items that eventually every person in the guild will have.  Most of the loot that we're talking about is stuff that less than 1% of a class will ever have.  I, for example, have a great belt dropped by Dracoliche -- a mob killable by most mid-power and higher guilds.  He's pretty much just a cross between a overgrown Ashenbone Drake from Hate and Venril Sathir.  A &quot;big Wuoshi with Lifetap instead of AE&quot; on his best day.  As much as I'd like to get that belt for every INT and WIS caster in the game, Dracoliche has a 13-item loot table and spawns once a week.  Even if we get a quarter of all of his spawns, and he drops the belt more than a quarter of the time, I can't get that good of a belt for all of my casters until sometime in 2005.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.gameznet.com/eq/equipment/ss/grotesquegirdle.jpg"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Who decides how much either has put into the guild? Who chooses which is more important? How do you do that if they both put the same time and effort into the guild? More importantly, how do you do so without spreading ill will around?  Putting a lot of time into a guild(as much as anyone else of your class) and being told &quot;You get the leftovers&quot; could be seen as, pardon me for saying it, &quot;A slap in the face.&quot;<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
You ask these questions like they're rhetorical and the answers are all obvious; that you do spread ill will around and make people into second-class citizens.<br>
<br>
So, I'll pretend you actually posed them as questions.  The guild as a whole, guided by the officers decides who deserves items.  In cases where all other things are equal, where no other determination exists, you try to let two (or more) people work it out themselves.  As a last resort, you flip a coin.  If for some reason Cantra and Vaxumgax are on a raid, both who have tirelessly given to the Shaman class and to Vision, and a great item dropped, I'd have absolute faith that first of all, they wouldn't need us to work it out.  Whatever Selan decided would sit well with either of them, and lacking his guiding hand, the two of them would be able to work it out.  In the rather unlikely event that I'm forced to work it out between the two of them, I'll simply make an arbitrary decision or flip a coin...  ...yes, you heard that right.  As a ~final~ solution and a last resort, I'd simply have one of 'em call it odd or even.<br>
<br>
Remember, none of our warrior are getting leftovers.  The gear that we've put on Allamar enables us to get better equipment than if we chose a pure /random strategy.  If the first 10 pieces of armor went to Allamar (which they didn't, but play along), then we're able to be more efficient in places like Temple of Veeshan.  Over the course of a few raids, we make up those 10 pieces and more for being a more efficient guild.  By giving up pieces in the short term to Allamar, all of our plate wearers benefit in the long term.<br>
<br>
A pure /random strategy doesn't enable a single tank to hold agro without becoming a liability.  With a BP on one tank, legs on another, arms on a third, and bracers on a 4th...  ....with no possibility for the warrior with a BP to get legs, since he has mediocre legs, and others in the guild have bad legs, no warrior ever stands out.  No warrior ever gets strong enough to make the raid efficient.<br>
<br>
